<div class="container">
    <h1>Welcome to Advanced Web Applications</h1>
    <p>In this chapter, we will explore advanced topics for building web applications in ASP.NET Core. These topics include:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Service Layer:</strong> Organizing business logic in a separate layer.</li>
        <li><strong>Controller and Repository Layers:</strong> Managing data access and user requests.</li>
        <li><strong>Authentication and Authorization:</strong> Managing user accounts, roles, and security.</li>
        <li><strong>Identity and Roles:</strong> Using ASP.NET Core Identity to handle login, registration, and role-based access.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Example Scenario</h2>
    <p>Imagine you are building an online store. Using advanced web app techniques, you can:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Protect admin pages so only managers can edit products.</li>
        <li>Separate the logic for fetching products from the controller using a service or repository layer.</li>
        <li>Handle user accounts and roles easily with ASP.NET Identity.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Exercise</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Create a new ASP.NET Core web app project.</li>
        <li>Add Identity to manage users and roles.</li>
        <li>Create a sample page that only an Admin can access.</li>
        <li>Use a simple service layer to return a list of items to display on a page.</li>
    </ul>

